Facts (layer 2):

`show` (VariableExpression):
  assigned type `Number -> ()`
  grouped with `value -> ()`
  has bound(s) `Describe` `Number` (resolved as `instance (Describe Number)`)
  has type `Number -> ()` or `Number Number Number -> ()`
  is an expression
  resolved to 1 definition(s): `show`

`show 1 2 3` (ExpressionStatement):
  assigned type `()`
  grouped with `show 1 2 3`
  has type `()`

`show 1 2 3` (CallExpression):
  grouped with `()`, `show 1 2 3`
  has type `()`
  is an expression

`1` (NumberExpression):
  assigned type `Number`
  grouped with `1`, `value`
  has type `Number`
  is an expression

`2` (NumberExpression):
  assigned type `Number`
  grouped with `2`
  has type `Number`
  is an expression

`3` (NumberExpression):
  assigned type `Number`
  grouped with `3`
  has type `Number`
  is an expression



Feedback:

`show` (conflicting-types)

  `show` is a `Number -> ()` or a `Number Number Number -> ()`, but it can only be one of these.

  1. `show`: `show` displays `1` on the screen.<wipple-hover-link>show :: value -> () where (Describe value)</wipple-hover-link> This requires `Describe` `Number`.

  2. `1`: `1` is a `Number`.

  3. `2`: `2` is a `Number`.

  4. `3`: `3` is a `Number`.

  (1 -> error, 2 -> 1)
